style="width:0.1%"></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3" style="background-color:#faf8f4;padding:2px 1pt;text-align:left;vertical-align:top"><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:110%">Jamie Dimon, Chairman and CEO, commented&#58; </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:110%">&#8220;The Firm concluded the year with a strong fourth quarter, generating net income of $14.0 billion.&#8221;</font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:110%">Dimon continued&#58; </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:110%">&#8220;Each line of business posted solid results. In the CIB, clients were active, with IB fees up 49%, and Markets revenue rose 21%. Additionally, Payments fees grew by double digits for the fourth consecutive quarter, helping drive Payments revenue to a record $18.1 billion for the year. In CCB, we continued to acquire new customers across Consumer Banking, Business Banking, Card and wealth management. For example, nearly 2 million net new checking accounts were opened during 2024. Finally, in AWM, management fees rose 21%, and revenue hit a record $5.8 billion. More impressively, client asset net inflows totaled $486 billion in 2024, bringing cumulative net inflows over the past two years to $976 billion.&#8221;</font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:110%">Dimon added&#58; </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:110%">&#8220;Regarding regulation, we have consistently said that regulation should be designed to effectively balance promoting economic growth and maintaining a safe and sound banking system. It is possible to achieve both goals. This is not about weakening regulation &#8212; we maintain a fortress balance sheet, evidenced by $547 billion of total loss-absorbing capacity and $1.4 trillion of cash and marketable securities &#8212; but rather about setting rules that are transparent, fair, holistic in their approach and based on rigorous data analysis, so that banks can play their critical role in the economy and markets.&#8221;</font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:110%">Dimon added&#58; </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:110%">&#8220;The U.S. economy has been resilient. Unemployment remains relatively low, and consumer spending stayed healthy, including during the holiday season. Businesses are more optimistic about the economy, and they are encouraged by expectations for a more pro-growth agenda and improved collaboration between government and business. However, two significant risks remain. Ongoing and future spending requirements will likely be inflationary, and therefore, inflation may persist for some time. Additionally, geopolitical conditions remain the most dangerous and complicated since World War II. As always, we hope for the best but prepare the Firm for a wide range of scenarios.&#8221;</font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:110%">Dimon concluded&#58; </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:400;line-height:110%">&#8220;I want to thank our exceptional employees across the globe. Their passion and dedication are what set us apart and enable us to be trusted partners for our clients and communities, which include consumers, small and large-sized businesses, schools, cities, states and countries.&#8221; </font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div><font><br></font></div></td></tr></table></div><div style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',sans-serif;font-size:8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> </font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;margin-top:3pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons Semibold',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Discussion of Results&#58;</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net income was $14.0 billion, up 50%.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net revenue was $43.7 billion, up 10%. Net interest income was $23.5 billion, down 3%. Noninterest revenue was $20.3 billion, up 29%. </font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net interest income excluding Markets</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:6.5pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;position:relative;top:-3.5pt;vertical-align:baseline">2</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> was $23.0 billion, down 2%, driven by lower rates and deposit margin compression across the lines of business, as well as lower deposit balances in CCB. This was largely offset by the impact of balance sheet actions, primarily securities reinvestment, as well as higher revolving balances in Card Services and higher wholesale deposit balances. Noninterest revenue excluding Markets</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:6.5pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;position:relative;top:-3.5pt;vertical-align:baseline">2</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> was $13.7 billion, up 30%, largely driven by higher asset management fees in AWM and CCB, higher investment banking fees and lower net investment securities losses compared to the prior year. Markets revenue was $7.0 billion, up 21%.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Noninterest expense was $22.8 billion, down 7%. Excluding the $2.9 billion FDIC special assessment in the prior year, noninterest expense was up 5%, predominantly driven by higher compensation, including growth in front office and technology employees, as well as higher brokerage expense and distribution fees.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">The provision for credit losses was $2.6 billion, reflecting net charge-offs of $2.4 billion and a net reserve build of $267 million. Net charge-offs of $2.4 billion were up $200 million, primarily driven by Card Services. The net reserve build included a $572 million net build in Consumer, predominantly in Card Services, and a $282 million net release in Wholesale. The prior-year provision was $2.8 billion, reflecting net charge-offs of $2.2 billion and a net reserve build of $598 million. </font></div><div style="height:42.75pt;position:relative;width:100%"><div style="bottom:0;position:absolute;width:100%"><div style="text-align:center"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net income was $4.5 billion, down 6%. </font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net revenue</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:6.5pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;position:relative;top:-3.5pt;vertical-align:baseline">13</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> was $18.4 billion, up 1%. Banking &#38; Wealth Management net revenue was $10.2 billion, down 7%, driven by lower net interest income on deposit margin compression and lower deposit balances, partially offset by higher asset management fees in J.P. Morgan Wealth Management. Home Lending net revenue was $1.3 billion, up 12%, predominantly driven by higher production revenue. Card Services &#38; Auto net revenue was $6.9 billion, up 14%, driven by Card Services, reflecting higher net interest income on higher revolving balances and higher card income on higher sales volume.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Noninterest expense was $9.7 billion, up 4%, predominantly driven by higher compensation for advisors and bankers, as well as higher technology expense. </font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">The provision for credit losses was $2.6 billion, reflecting net charge-offs of $2.1 billion and a net reserve build of $557 million. Net charge-offs of $2.1 billion were up $428 million, driven by Card Services, primarily due to the seasoning of vintages originated in recent years and balance growth. The net reserve build was predominantly in Card Services, driven by growth in revolving balances, partially offset by changes in certain macroeconomic variables. The prior-year provision was $2.2 billion, reflecting net charge-offs of $1.6 billion and a net reserve build of $551 million.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="height:45pt;position:relative;width:100%"><div style="bottom:0;position:absolute;width:100%"><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;margin-top:5.7pt;text-align:justify"><font style="background-color:#ffffff;color:#000000;font-family:'Sons Semibold',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Discussion of Results</font><font style="background-color:#ffffff;color:#000000;font-family:'Sons Semibold',sans-serif;font-size:6.5pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%;position:relative;top:-3.5pt;vertical-align:baseline">7</font><font style="background-color:#ffffff;color:#000000;font-family:'Sons Semibold',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">&#58;</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="background-color:#ffffff;color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net income was $6.6 billion, up 59%. </font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net revenue was $17.6 billion, up 18%. Banking &#38; Payments revenue was $9.3 billion, up 15%. Investment Banking revenue was $2.6 billion, up 46%. Investment Banking fees were up 49%, driven by higher fees across all products. Payments revenue was $4.7 billion, up 6%. Excluding the net impact of equity investments, Payments revenue was up 3%, driven by higher deposit balances and fee growth, largely offset by deposit margin compression. Lending revenue was $1.9 billion, up 9%, predominantly driven by lower losses on hedges of the retained lending portfolio.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Markets &#38; Securities Services revenue was $8.3 billion, up 20%. Markets revenue was $7.0 billion, up 21%. Fixed Income Markets revenue was $5.0 billion, up 20%, largely driven by higher revenue in Credit and Currencies &#38; Emerging Markets. Equity Markets revenue was $2.0 billion, up 22%, predominantly driven by higher client activity in Derivatives and Cash. Securities Services revenue was $1.3 billion, up 10%, driven by fee growth on higher client activity and market levels, as well as higher deposit balances.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Noninterest expense was $8.7 billion, up 7%, predominan</font><font style="background-color:#ffffff;color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">tly driven by</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> higher brokerage,</font><font style="background-color:#ffffff;color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> technology and legal expense</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="background-color:#ffffff;color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">The provision for credit losses was $61 million, reflecting net charge-offs of $300 million and a net reserve release of $239 million. The provision was driven by net downgrade activity and the net impact of charge-offs, largely offset by a reserve release due to an update to loss assumptions on certain loans in Markets. The prior-year provision was $576 million, reflecting a net reserve build of $329 million and net charge-offs of $247 million. </font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div fees.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Assets style="text-align:center"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',sans-serif;font-size:8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> </font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;margin-top:3pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons Semibold',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-style:italic;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Discussion of Results&#58;  </font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net income was $1.3 billion, compared with a net loss of $875 million in the prior year. </font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Net revenue</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:6.5pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;position:relative;top:-3.5pt;vertical-align:baseline">13</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> was $2.0 billion, up $223 million. Net interest income was $2.0 billion, down $415 million, driven by lower rates, largely offset by the impact of balance sheet actions, primarily securities reinvestment. Noninterest revenue was a net loss of $30 million, compared with a net loss of $668 million in the prior year, driven by lower net investment securities losses.</font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Noninterest expense was $550 million, down $3.0 billion, predominantly driven by the absence of the $2.9 billion FDIC special assessment in the prior year. </font></div><div style="margin-top:6pt;text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="height:45pt;position:relative;width:100%"><div style="bottom:0;position:absolute;width:100%"><div style="text-align:center"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">5 </font></div></div></div><div id="ibf097e71f39e4dc38adce64219f2c4ea_19"></div><hr style="page-break-after:always"><div style="min-height:45pt;width:100%"><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'JPMC Tiempos',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">JPMorgan&#160;Chase &#38; Co.</font></div><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'JPMC Tiempos',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">News Release </font></div></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">2.    </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons Semibold',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Notes on non-GAAP financial measures&#58;</font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">a.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:10.51pt">The Firm prepares its Consolidated Financial Statements in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the U.S. (&#8220;U.S. GAAP&#8221;). That presentation, which is referred to as &#8220;reported&#8221; basis, provides the reader with an understanding of the Firm&#8217;s results that can be tracked consistently from year-to-year and enables a comparison of the Firm&#8217;s performance with the U.S. GAAP financial statements of other companies. In addition to analyzing the Firm&#8217;s results on a reported basis, management reviews Firmwide results, including the overhead ratio, on a &#8220;managed&#8221; basis&#59; these Firmwide managed basis results are non-GAAP financial measures. The Firm also reviews the results of the lines of business on a managed basis. The Firm&#8217;s definition of managed basis starts, in each case, with the reported U.S. GAAP results and includes certain reclassifications to present total net revenue for the Firm as a whole and for each of the reportable business segments and Corporate on a fully taxable-equivalent basis. Accordingly, revenue from investments that receive tax credits and tax-exempt securities is presented in the managed results on a basis comparable to taxable investments and securities. These financial measures allow management to assess the comparability of revenue from year-to-year arising from both taxable and tax-exempt sources. The corresponding income tax impact related to tax-exempt items is recorded within income tax expense. These adjustments have no impact on net income as reported by the Firm as a whole or by each of the lines of business and Corporate. For a reconciliation of the Firm&#8217;s results from a reported to managed basis, refer to page 7 of the Earnings Release Financial Supplement.</font></div><div style="padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font><br></font></div><div style="padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">b.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:9.83pt">Tangible common equity (&#8220;TCE&#8221;), return on tangible common equity (&#8220;ROTCE&#8221;) and tangible book value per share (&#8220;TBVPS&#8221;) are each non-GAAP financial measures. TCE represents the Firm&#8217;s common stockholders&#8217; equity (i.e., total stockholders&#8217; equity less preferred stock) less goodwill and identifiable intangible assets (other than mortgage servicing rights), net of related deferred tax liabilities. For a reconciliation from common stockholders&#8217; equity to TCE, refer to page 10 of the Earnings Release Financial Supplement. ROTCE measures the Firm&#8217;s net income applicable to common equity as a percentage of average TCE. TBVPS represents the Firm&#8217;s TCE at period-end divided by common shares at period-end. Book value per share was $116.07, $115.15 and $104.45 at December 31, 2024, September 30, 2024, and December 31, 2023, respectively. TCE, ROTCE, and TBVPS are utilized by the Firm, as well as investors and analysts, in assessing the Firm&#8217;s use of equity.</font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">c.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:10.57pt">In addition to reviewing net interest income (&#8220;NII&#8221;) and noninterest revenue (&#8220;NIR&#8221;) on a managed basis, management also reviews these metrics excluding Markets, which is composed of Fixed Income Markets and Equity Markets. Markets revenue consists of principal transactions, fees, commissions and other income, as well as net interest income. These metrics, which exclude Markets, are non-GAAP financial measures. Management reviews these metrics to assess the performance of the Firm&#8217;s lending, investing (including asset-liability management) and deposit-raising activities, apart from any volatility associated with Markets activities. In addition, management also assesses Markets business performance on a total revenue basis as offsets may occur across revenue lines. For example, securities that generate net interest income may be risk-managed by derivatives that are reflected at fair value in principal transactions revenue. Management believes these measures provide investors and analysts with alternative measures to analyze the revenue trends of the Firm. For a reconciliation of NII and NIR from reported to excluding Markets, refer to page 28 of the Earnings Release Financial Supplement. For additional information on Markets revenue, refer to page 75 of the Firm&#8217;s 2023 Form 10-K.</font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">d.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:9.84pt">Full-year 2024 results included the impact of significant items. These items collectively refer to a $7.9 billion net gain related to Visa shares, a $1.0 billion donation of Visa shares to pre-fund contributions to the Firm&#8217;s Foundation, $546 million of net investment securities losses and a $725 million increase to the estimated FDIC special assessment, all of which were previously disclosed in the first and second quarters of 2024. Full-year 2024 revenue, net income, earnings per share and ROTCE excluding significant items are non-GAAP financial measures. Excluding these items resulted in a decrease of $7.3 billion to reported revenue from $177.6 billion to $170.2 billion, a decrease of $7.3 billion to managed revenue from $180.6 billion to $173.3 billion, a decrease of $4.5 billion (after tax) to reported net income from $58.5 billion to $54.0 billion, a decrease of $1.53 per share to reported EPS from $19.75 to $18.22 and a decrease of 2ppts to reported ROTCE from 22% to 20%. Management believes these measures provide useful information to investors and analysts in assessing the Firm&#8217;s results.</font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="height:45pt;position:relative;width:100%"><div style="bottom:0;position:absolute;width:100%"><div style="text-align:center"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">6 </font></div></div></div><div id="ibf097e71f39e4dc38adce64219f2c4ea_22"></div><hr style="page-break-after:always"><div style="min-height:45pt;width:100%"><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'JPMC Tiempos',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">JPMorgan&#160;Chase &#38; Co.</font></div><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'JPMC Tiempos',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">News Release </font></div></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons Semibold',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%"> Additional notes&#58;</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font><br></font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">3.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:10.07pt">Estimated. Reflects the Current Expected Credit Losses (&#8220;CECL&#8221;) capital transition provisions. As of December 31, 2024, CET1 capital and Total Loss-Absorbing Capacity reflected the remaining $720 million CECL benefit. Refer to&#160;Note 21 of the Firm&#8217;s Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended September 30, 2024 and Note 27 of the Firm&#8217;s 2023 Form 10-K for additional information.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">4.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:9.75pt">Estimated. Cash and marketable securities includes end-of-period eligible high-quality liquid assets (&#8220;HQLA&#8221;), excluding regulatory prescribed haircuts under the liquidity coverage ratio (&#8220;LCR&#8221;) rule where applicable, for both the Firm and the excess HQLA-eligible securities included as part of the excess liquidity at JPMorgan Chase Bank, N.A., which are not transferable to non-bank affiliates and thus excluded from the Firm&#8217;s LCR. Also includes other end-of-period unencumbered marketable securities, such as equity and debt securities. Does not include borrowing capacity at Federal Home Loan Banks and the discount window at the Federal Reserve Bank. Refer to Liquidity Risk Management on pages 50-57 of the Firm&#8217;s Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended September 30, 2024 and pages 102-109 of the Firm&#8217;s 2023 Form 10-K for additional information.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">5.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:10.07pt">Excludes Commercial Card.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">6.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:9.88pt">Users of all mobile platforms who have logged in within the past 90 days.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">7.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:10.44pt">Effective in the second quarter of 2024, the Firm reorganized its reportable business segments by combining the former Corporate &#38; Investment Bank and Commercial Banking business segments to form one segment, the Commercial &#38; Investment Bank (&#34;CIB&#34;).</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">8.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:9.79pt">Client deposits and other third party liabilities (&#8220;client deposits&#8221;) pertain to the Payments and Securities Services businesses.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">9.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:9.88pt">Assets under management (&#8220;AUM&#8221;).</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">10.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:5.78pt">Includes the net impact of employee issuances. Excludes excise tax and commissions.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">11.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:8.25pt">Last twelve months (&#8220;LTM&#8221;).</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">12.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:6.42pt">Credit provided to clients represents new and renewed credit, including loans and lending-related commitments, as well as unused amounts of advised uncommitted lines of credit where the Firm has discretion on whether or not to make a loan under these lines. Credit and capital for corporations and non-U.S. government entities includes Individuals and Individual Entities primarily consisting of Global Private Bank clients within AWM.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;padding-left:18pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%">13.</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:112%;padding-left:6.31pt">During the fourth quarter of 2024, the Firm made a change to its funds transfer pricing with respect to consumer deposits, resulting in an increase in the funding benefit reflected within CCB net interest income which is fully offset within Corporate net interest income. </font></div><div style="width:100.000%"><div style="display:inline-block;vertical-align:top;width:46.491%"><div><font><br></font></div></div><div style="display:inline-block;max-width:7.017%;min-width:6.017%;vertical-align:top"></div><div style="display:inline-block;vertical-align:top;width:46.492%"></div></div><div style="margin-bottom:6pt;text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="height:45pt;position:relative;width:100%"><div style="bottom:0;position:absolute;width:100%"><div style="text-align:center"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Times New Roman',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">7 </font></div></div></div><hr style="page-break-after:always"><div style="min-height:45pt;width:100%"><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'JPMC Tiempos',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">JPMorgan&#160;Chase &#38; Co.</font></div><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'JPMC Tiempos',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">News Release </font></div></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">JPMorgan Chase &#38; Co. (NYSE&#58; JPM) is a leading financial services firm based in the United States of America (&#8220;U.S.&#8221;), with operations worldwide. JPMorganChase had</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:12pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">$4.0 trillion in assets and $345&#160;billion in stockholders&#8217; equity as of December 31, 2024. The Firm is a leader in investment banking, financial services for consumers and small businesses, commercial banking, financial transaction processing and asset management. Under the J.P. Morgan and Chase brands, the Firm serves millions of customers predominantly in the U.S., and many of the world&#8217;s most prominent corporate, institutional and government clients globally. Information about JPMorgan Chase &#38; Co. is available at </font><font style="color:#4f81bd;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">www.jpmorganchase.com</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">.</font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font><br></font></div><div style="text-align:justify"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Sons',sans-serif;font-size:10pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">JPMorgan Chase &#38; Co. will host a conference call today, January 15, 2025, at 8&#58;30 a.m. (ET) to present fourth-quarter and full-year 2024 financial results. The general public can access the call by dialing (888) 324-3618 in the U.S. and Canada, or (312) 470-7119 for international callers&#59; use passcode 1364784#. style="margin-bottom:6pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">On May&#160;1, 2023, JPMorganChase acquired certain assets and assumed certain liabilities of First Republic Bank from the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (&#8220;FDIC&#8221;).</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Pre-provision profit, TBVPS and ROTCE are each non-GAAP financial measures. Tangible common equity (&#8220;TCE&#8221;) is also a non-GAAP financial measure&#59; refer to page 10 for a reconciliation of common stockholders&#8217; equity to TCE. Refer to page 28 for a further discussion of these measures. </font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(b)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Refer to Reconciliation from Reported to Managed Basis on page 7 for a further discussion of managed basis.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(c)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:2.02pt">Ratios are based upon annualized amounts.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:107%">(d)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:107%;padding-left:1.69pt">The capital metrics reflect the Current Expected Credit Losses (&#34;CECL&#34;) capital transition provisions. As of December 31, 2024, September 30, 2024, June 30, 2024 and March 31, 2024, CET1 capital reflected the remaining $720 million CECL benefit&#59; as of December 31, 2023, CET1 capital reflected a $1.4 billion benefit. Refer to&#160;Note 21 of the Firm&#8217;s Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended September 30, 2024, and Note 27 of the Firm&#8217;s 2023 Form 10-K for additional information.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(e)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Reflect the Firm&#8217;s ratios under the Basel III Standardized approach. Refer to page 9 for further information on the Firm&#8217;s capital metrics. </font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(f)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:3.36pt">Estimated.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(g)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Included a $7.9 billion net gain related to Visa shares. Refer to Note 2 of the Firm&#8217;s Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended June 30, 2024 for additional information on the exchange offer for Visa Class B-1 common stock.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:3pt;padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(h)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Included the FDIC special assessment to recover estimated losses to the Deposit Insurance Fund of $725 million for the three months ended March 31, 2024, which reflects</font><font style="color:#ee2724;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">an adjustment to the $2.9 billion estimate recorded in the three months ended December 31, 2023. style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">On May&#160;1, 2023, JPMorganChase acquired certain assets and assumed certain liabilities of First Republic Bank from the FDIC. </font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(a)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Refer to Commercial &#38; Investment Bank VaR on page 19 for further information.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(b)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Earnings-at-risk estimates the Firm&#8217;s interest rate exposure for a given interest rate scenario. It is presented as a sensitivity to a baseline, which includes net interest income and certain interest rate sensitive fees. The baseline reflects certain assumptions relating to the Federal Reserve&#8217;s balance sheet policy (e.g., quantitative tightening and usage at the Reverse Repurchase Facility) that require management judgment. The Firm&#8217;s actual net interest income for the rate shifts presented may differ as the earnings-at-risk scenarios are modelled as instantaneous shifts and exclude any actions that could be taken by the Firm or its clients and customers in response to instantaneous rate changes. Other significant assumptions in the earnings-at-risk scenarios may also differ from actual results, including mortgage prepayments and deposits rates paid. Refer to pages 80-81 of the Firm&#8217;s Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended September 30, 2024 for additional information.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(c)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:2.02pt">Reflects the simultaneous shift of U.S. dollar and non-U.S. dollar rates. At September 30, 2024, June 30, 2024, March 31, 2024 and December 31, 2023, represents the total of the Firm&#8217;s U.S. dollar and non-U.S. dollar sensitivities. Refer to Structural interest rate risk management of the Firm&#8217;s Quarterly Reports on Form 10-Q for the quarterly periods ended September 30, 2024, June 30, 2024 and March 31, 2024 and the Firm&#8217;s 2023 Form 10-K for additional information.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(d)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Refer to Reconciliation from Reported to Managed Basis on page 7 for a further discussion of managed basis.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(e)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Effective in the second quarter of 2024, the Firm reorganized its reportable business segments by combining the former Corporate &#38; Investment Bank and Commercial Banking business segments to form one segment, the Commercial &#38; Investment Bank (&#34;CIB&#34;). Refer to Business Segment Results on page 20 of the Firm&#8217;s Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended June 30, 2024 for additional information.'</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(f)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:3.36pt">Estimated.</font></div><div 2023, JPMorganChase acquired certain assets and assumed certain liabilities of First Republic Bank from the FDIC. </font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(a)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Effective January 1, 2024, the Firm adopted updates to the Accounting for Investments in Tax Credit Structures Using the Proportional Amortization Method guidance, under the modified retrospective method. The amortization of the associated investments that was previously recognized in other income is now recognized in income tax expense, which aligns with the associated tax credits and other tax benefits. Refer to Note 1 and 5 of the Firm&#8217;s Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended March 31, 2024 for additional information.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(b)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Included Firmwide legal expense of $236 million, $259 million, $317 million, $(72) million and $175 million for the three months ended December 31, 2024, September 30, 2024, June 30, 2024, March 31, 2024 and December 31, 2023, respectively, and $740 million and $1.4 billion for the full year 2024 and 2023, respectively.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(c)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:2.02pt">Ratios are based upon annualized amounts.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(d)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Refer to page 28 for a further discussion of ROTCE.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(e)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Included a $7.9 billion net gain related to Visa shares. Refer to footnote (g) on page 2 for further information.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(f)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:3.36pt">Included a $1.0 billion donation of Visa shares to pre-fund contributions to the JPMorganChase Foundation.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(g)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Included an FDIC special assessment to recover estimated losses to the Deposit Insurance Fund of $725 million for the three months ended March 31, 2024, which was an adjustment to the $2.9 billion estimate recorded in the three months ended December 31, 2023. Refer to&#160;Note 6 on page 220 of the Firm&#8217;s 2023 Form 10-K for additional information. </font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(h)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Included an income tax benefit of $463 million and $428 million for the three months and full year ended December&#160;31, 2023, respectively, related to the finalization of certain income tax regulations. The benefit resulted in a reduction in the Firm&#8217;s effective tax rate of 4.1 percentage points in the fourth quarter of 2023. </font></div><div style="text-indent:9pt"><font><br></font></div><div style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">The Firm prepares its Consolidated Financial Statements using accounting principles generally accepted in the U.S. (&#8220;U.S. GAAP&#8221;). That presentation, which is referred to as &#8220;reported&#8221; basis, provides the reader with an understanding of the Firm&#8217;s results that can be tracked consistently from year-to-year and enables a comparison of the Firm&#8217;s performance with other companies&#8217; U.S. GAAP financial statements. In addition to analyzing the Firm&#8217;s results on a reported basis, management reviews Firmwide results, including the overhead ratio, on a &#8220;managed&#8221; basis&#59; these Firmwide managed basis results are non-GAAP financial measures. The Firm also reviews the results of the lines of business on a managed basis. Refer to the notes on Non-GAAP Financial Measures on page 28 for additional information on managed basis.</font></div><div><font><br></font></div><div><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Includes assets invested in managed accounts and J.P. Morgan mutual funds where AWM is the investment manager. Refer to AWM segment results on pages 20-22 for additional information.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font billion, $7.6 billion and $8.6 billion for the three months ended December 31, 2024, September 30, 2024, June 30, 2024, March 31, 2024 and December 31, 2023, respectively, and $47.4 billion and $41.4 style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(a)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Allowance for loan losses of $435 million, $366 million, $452 million, $375 million and $251 million were held against these nonaccrual loans at December 31, 2024, September 30, 2024, June 30, 2024, March 31, 2024 and December 31, 2023, respectively.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(b)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Excludes mortgage loans past due and insured by U.S. government agencies, which are primarily 90 or more days past due. These loans have been excluded based upon the government guarantee. At December 31, 2024, September 30, 2024, June 30, 2024, March 31, 2024 and December 31, 2023, mortgage loans 90 or more days past due and insured by U.S. government agencies were $37 million, $38 million, $42 million, $50 million and $59 million, respectively.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(c)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:2.02pt">Loans held-for-sale and loans at fair value were excluded when calculating the net charge-off&#47;(recovery) rate.</font></div><div style="text-indent:9pt"><font colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" 1pt"></td></tr></table></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(a)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Client deposits and other third-party liabilities pertain to the Payments and Securities Services businesses.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(b)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">The impact of the CIB business segment reorganization was not material to Total CIB VaR. Prior periods have not been revised. Refer to Business Segment Results on page 20 of the Firm&#8217;s Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended June 30, 2024 for additional information.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(c)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:2.02pt">CIB trading VaR includes substantially all market-making and client-driven activities, as well as certain risk management activities in CIB, including credit spread sensitivity to CVA. Refer to VaR measurement on pages 137&#8211;139 of the Firm&#8217;s 2023 Form 10-K for further information and pages 77&#8211;79 of the Firm&#8217;s Quarterly Report on Form 10-Q for the quarterly period ended September 30, 2024 for further information.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(d)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Diversification benefit represents the difference between the portfolio VaR and the sum of its individual components. This reflects the non-additive nature of VaR due to imperfect correlation across CIB risks.</font></div><div style="padding-left:9pt;text-indent:-9pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(e)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Credit Portfolio VaR includes the derivative CVA, hedges of the CVA and credit protection purchased against certain retained loans and lending-related commitments, which are reported in principal transactions revenue. This VaR does not include the retained loan portfolio, which is not reported at fair value. In line with the Firm's internal model governance, the credit risk component of CVA related to certain counterparties was removed from Credit Portfolio VaR due to the widening of the credit spreads for those counterparties to elevated levels. The related hedges were also removed to maintain consistency. This exposure is now reflected in other sensitivity-based measures.</font></div><div style="height:18pt;position:relative;width:100%"><div style="bottom:0;position:absolute;width:100%"><div style="text-align:right"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> Page 19</font></div></div></div><div style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:6pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:1.69pt">Excludes mortgage loans past due and insured by U.S. government agencies, which are primarily 90 or more days past due. These loans have been excluded based upon the government guarantee. At December 31, 2024, September 30, 2024, June 30, 2024, March 31, 2024 and December 31, 2023, mortgage loans 90 or more days past due and insured by U.S. government agencies were $121 million, $126 million, $138 million, $157 million and $182 million, respectively. In addition, the Firm&#8217;s policy is generally to exempt credit card loans from being placed on nonaccrual status as permitted by regulatory guidance. Refer to Note 12 of the Firm&#8217;s 2023 Form 10-K for additional information on the Firm&#8217;s credit card nonaccrual and charge-off policies.</font></div><div style="height:23px;margin-bottom:5pt;vertical-align:text-bottom;width:163px"></div></td></tr><tr style="height:9pt"><td colspan="9" style="padding:2px 1pt;text-align:left;vertical-align:bottom"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8pt;font-weight:700;line-height:100%">NON-GAAP FINANCIAL MEASURES</font></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td></tr><tr style="height:9pt"><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td><td colspan="3" style="padding:0 1pt"></td></tr></table></div><div style="margin-bottom:2pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">Non-GAAP Financial Measures</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:2pt;padding-left:18pt;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(a)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:7.25pt">In addition to analyzing the Firm&#8217;s results on a reported basis, management reviews Firmwide results, including the overhead ratio, on a </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">&#8220;managed&#8221; basis</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">&#59; these Firmwide managed basis results are non-GAAP financial measures. The Firm also reviews the results of the lines of business on a managed basis. The Firm&#8217;s definition of managed basis starts, in each case, with the reported U.S. GAAP results and includes certain reclassifications to present total net revenue for the Firm as a whole and for each of the reportable business segments and Corporate on an FTE basis. Accordingly, revenue from investments that receive tax credits and tax-exempt securities is presented in the managed results on a basis comparable to taxable investments and securities. These financial measures allow management to assess the comparability of revenue from year-to-year arising from both taxable and tax-exempt sources. The corresponding income tax impact related to tax-exempt items is recorded within income tax expense. These adjustments have no impact on net income as reported by the Firm as a whole or by each of the lines of business and Corporate.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:2pt;padding-left:18pt;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(b)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%;padding-left:7.25pt">Pre-provision profit </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">is a non-GAAP financial measure which represents total net revenue less total noninterest expense. The Firm believes that this financial measure is useful in assessing the ability of a lending institution to generate income in excess of its provision for credit losses.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:2pt;padding-left:18pt;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(c)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%;padding-left:7.74pt">TCE, ROTCE, and TBVPS</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> are each non-GAAP financial measures. TCE represents the Firm&#8217;s common stockholders&#8217; equity (i.e., total stockholders&#8217; equity less preferred stock) less goodwill and identifiable intangible assets (other than MSRs), net of related deferred tax liabilities. ROTCE measures the Firm&#8217;s net income applicable to common equity as a percentage of average TCE. TBVPS represents the Firm&#8217;s TCE at period-end divided by common shares at period-end. TCE, ROTCE, and TBVPS are utilized by the Firm, as well as investors and analysts, in assessing the Firm&#8217;s use of equity.</font></div><div style="margin-bottom:2pt;padding-left:18pt;text-indent:-18pt"><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">(d)</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%;padding-left:7.25pt">In addition to reviewing net interest income (&#8220;NII&#8221;), net yield, and noninterest revenue (&#8220;NIR&#8221;) on a managed basis, management also reviews these metrics </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:700;line-height:120%">excluding Markets</font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">, which is composed of Fixed Income Markets and Equity Markets, as shown below. Markets revenue consists of principal transactions, fees, commissions and other income, as well as net interest income.These metrics, which exclude</font><font style="color:#ee2724;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%"> </font><font style="color:#000000;font-family:'Arial',sans-serif;font-size:8.8pt;font-weight:400;line-height:120%">Markets, are non-GAAP financial measures. Management reviews these metrics to assess the performance of the Firm&#8217;s lending, investing (including asset-liability management) and deposit-raising activities, apart from any volatility associated with Markets activities. In addition, management also assesses Markets business performance on a total revenue basis as offsets may occur across revenue lines. For example, securities that generate net interest income may be risk-managed by derivatives that are reflected at fair value in principal transactions revenue. Management believes these measures provide investors and analysts with alternative measures to analyze the revenue trends of the Firm. For additional information on Markets revenue, refer to page 75 of the Firm&#8217;s 2023 Form 10-K.</font></div><div style="padding-left:18pt"><table var Show={};Show.LastAR=null,Show.showAR=function(a,r,w){if(Show.LastAR)Show.hideAR();var e=a;while(e&&e.nodeName!='TABLE')e=e.nextSibling;if(!e||e.nodeName!='TABLE'){var ref=((window)?w.document:document).getElementById(r);if(ref){e=ref.cloneNode(!0);
e.removeAttribute('id');a.parentNode.appendChild(e)}}
if(e)e.style.display='block';Show.LastAR=e};Show.hideAR=function(){Show.LastAR.style.display='none'};Show.toggleNext=function(a){var e=a;while(e.nodeName!='DIV')e=e.nextSibling;if(!e.style){}else if(!e.style.display){}else{var d,p_;if(e.style.display=='none'){d='block';p='-'}else{d='none';p='+'}
e.style.display=d;if(a.textContent){a.textContent=p+a.textContent.substring(1)}else{a.innerText=p+a.innerText.substring(1)}}}
